                <div class="accordion-item__content" id="" aria-hidden="true">
                    <p>All developers (including external agencies or partners) who wish to use the DPL to build a product must first organise a kick-off meeting with the digital communications team. You should set up this meeting as soon as possible near the start of your project (within the appraise or define stages).</p>
                    <p>At this meeting, you will agree on the rules, responsibilities and sign-off gateways with the digital communications team. These include:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>information architecture (for web pages)</li>
                        <li>workflows (for web applications)</li>
                        <li>adherence to digital standards, including user-centred design, content management, URL policy, house style, and corporate identity</li>
                        <li>training.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>At this meeting, you will provide clear written commitment that no new product using the DPL will go live without the explicit, written sign-off by the digital communications team.</p>
                </div>
            </li>
    <li class="accordion-item">
                <div class="accordion-item__toggle">
                    <h3 class="accordion-item__toggle-title">
                        <button class="accordion-item__toggle-button">Developing new patterns</button>
                    </h3>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-item__content" id="" aria-hidden="true">
                    <p>To ensure design integrity and consistency of experience for our website users you must agree to the following:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>New patterns must be created only by developers working directly alongside the digital communications team.</li>
                        <li>No patterns or elements (such as colours) in the DPL may be edited without first liaising with the digital communications team.</li>
                        <li>CSS or JavaScript must not be used to overrule DPL elements, patterns, fonts, etc.</li>
                        <li>Developers using the DPL must not fork the version controlled repository.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </li>
